The paper discusses the use of genetic algorithms (GAs) to solve dynamic problems, which are often encountered in the field of computational intelligence. The paper specifically focuses on the use of dissortative mating GAs, which have been shown to be effective in maintaining genetic diversity and escaping local optima traps. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of adaptive threshold values to select parents for crossover, which is a common technique in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also involves the analysis of experimental results, which suggests that it may belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the optimization of dynamic systems, which suggests that it may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
